    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1948-06-03T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1948-06-03T00:00:00-05:00" n="83"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d83">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">834.00/6–348: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Paraguay</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Warren</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">III. PARAGUAY</seg>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Asunción</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1948-06-03">June 3,
                            1948</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>263. President Morinigo<note n="1" xml:id="d83fn1">Gen. Higinio Morinigo.</note>
                    resigned at 0030 on demand of Felipe <pb facs="0125" n="109" xml:id="pg_109"/>
                    Molas Lopez<note n="2" xml:id="d83fn2">Interventor of the National
                        University.</note> and Mario Mallorquin<note n="3" xml:id="d83fn3">Director
                        of Lands and Colonization.</note> representing the civil forces of the
                    revolution and in obedience to instruction from Colonel Montanaro, Military
                        Commander<note n="4" xml:id="d83fn4">Col. Carlos Montanaro, Asunción
                        garrison commander. Other leaders of the police–army coup were Chief of
                        Police Liberto Rodríguez, Maj. Adalberto Canata, Commander of one of the
                        Cavalry Regiments, and Abel Dos Santos, Mayor of Asunción. (Despatch 297,
                        June 15, from Asunción, 834.00/6–1548.)</note> of the revolt. President
                    Supreme Court Juan Manuel Frutos takes oath this morning as Provisional
                    President.…</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Warren</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
